@node "install" "Installation"
 INSTALLATION:

The following must be installed and running for MM to function:

   AmiTCP 3.0 or better
   PutMail (available on Aminet and this archive)
   InetUtils1.4

CanDo 2.0 or better can be installed so that you do not need the larger
executable,  but it is not required if you have downloaded the linked
version.


AmiTCP must be installed and you should have had some experience with SMTPpost
in order for most of this to work. The reason is that if you have gone through
the  pain of making sure that all necessary variables are set in your ENV:
directory then  MM should load right up with a couple of additions.

You should also have the SMTPd running from InetUtils1.4 because it handles
incoming mail to your system. It must write to UUMAIL: until I figure out a
better way to handle the destination drawer.

Oh, yeah. This was designed to work with a SLIP connection. I'm not sure why
anyone would want to use it in a closed LAN situation, but hey, what do I
know? UUCP may work, but all of those mail files would sit until you poll your
provider.

NEXT:

1-Place MM wherever you wish.

2-Make an assign for MM:
     assign MM: <anydirectory>

3-Set the environmental variable SMTPHOST. This can be set from your
user-startup  or manually like:

   setenv SMTPHOST server0.cybernetics.net

This is just an example so make sure that you have entered your own server.

4- Follow the directions for creating a mailing list.
@endnode

@node "config" "Configuring"
 The screen with the simple editor is very similar to the logs screen. You can
change any text from the config file, but the same constraints apply.  If the
file says DO NOT do something, then please do not do it.  Spacing is critical
here.  You are allowed to save or go back to the main window from here.
@endnode

@node "list" "ListĀCreation"


                              CREATING A LIST


MM can address up to 10 mailing lists. The OWNER<#> variable handles the
address of the managing part of MM. For example, when a message come through
requesting a subscription, it is saved under this name. MM then parses out the
command and deletes the file, adding the sender to the corresponding LIST<#>.

OWNER1 owner-programming LIST1 programming

A request for subbing comes in to owner-programming. All postings to the list
come to programming.  Be sure to leave the <NONE> if there is no list for a
number. MM uses the <NONE> setting.

When a message comes in to programming, MM grabs it from MAILDIR(CURRENTLY
UUMAIL:), to T:, deletes the original, and mails it out to everyone in the
file  programming.names which is stored in MM:LISTS/.

When you create the file <file>.names, be sure to have one address per line.
When a SUBSCRIBE command comes in to the OWNER<#>, the sender is automatically
added to the .names file.  UNSUBSCRIBE will remove them.

I suggest that you use the same system that I use for the OWNER<#>.  put
"owner-" and append the same name that you give LIST<#>. If you do not use the
same  name then the sender will not be added to the correct list.
@endnode

@node "mainwindow" "TheĀMainĀWindow"


THE MAIN PROGRAM

When first opened you will see a small window with TWO text area and two
buttons.

   @{"LOGS" link "logs" 0}
   @{"CNFG" link "cnfg" 0}

LOGS will show you the file designated as your logfile. See the log section.
Here you may clear the log if you wish, or go back to the MAIN window.

CNFG will allow you to edit some of your settings, in fact all of them, in a
text editor environment.
@endnode

@node "sub" "Sub/Unsub"


                     SUBSCRIBING and UNSUBSCRIBING

When a message comes in for owner-<list>, MM will scan the Subject: header for
the word SUBSCRIBE or UNSUBSCRIBE.  Depending on which is read will determine
which event takes place.
@endnode

@node "sig" "Signatures"


                             SIGNATURES

If you want a signature to be appended to outgoing messages then create the
file  <list>.sig in the sigs directory.  It will be tacked on before sending.
@endnode

